{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_016vhfASyqfW5SV5VxZeqHpA","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the full picture:\n1. The StatefulSet sets `POD_NAME` env var via the Kubernetes downward API (`metadata.name`).\n2. The ConfigMap is mounted as a file directly into the container.\n3. The ConfigMap has `node.name: ${POD_NAME}` which Elasticsearch resolves using its own environment variable substitution.\n\nBut the precondition script ran:\n```bash\nkubectl -n elasticsearch apply -f - <<EOF\n...\n    node.name: ${POD_NAME}\n...\nEOF\n```\n\nSince `${POD_NAME}` was in a heredoc, the shell expanded it before sending to kubectl. Since `POD_NAME` wasn't set in the shell environment at that point, it became empty, leaving just `node.name: ` with no value. I need to fix this by escaping the variable so it reaches Elasticsearch literally—either with `\\${POD_NAME}` in the patch, applying from a file, or using `kubectl patch` with proper escaping. I also notice the seed hosts reference `default.svc.cluster.local` but the namespace is actually `elasticsearch`, so those need to be corrected to point to the right namespace.\n\nBut wait—the two running nodes are working fine, which means they must have loaded the original ConfigMap before the precondition script broke it. The script then applied a corrupted ConfigMap with the wrong namespace in the seed hosts and deleted the third node's PVC, forcing it to start fresh with the broken config. So es-cluster-0 and es-cluster-1 are still using their cached configuration from disk, while es-cluster-2 is stuck trying to bootstrap with the incorrect settings.\n\nThe seed hosts mismatch (`default.svc.cluster.local` instead of `elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`) shouldn't affect the two running nodes since they're already clustered together, but it could be a problem for es-cluster-2 trying to rejoin—except the node is actually crashing earlier than that because the `node.name` field is empty.\n\nI need to fix both issues: set `node.name` to use the actual pod name instead of the literal `${POD_NAME}` string, and correct the seed_hosts to point to the right namespace. Let me check the original resource file to see what the configuration should be.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2278,"cache_read_input_tokens":34001,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2278},"output_tokens":31,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8f7e58f3-8ff3-440c-a527-37d4f124d3d5","uuid":"f1e0e970-37da-4d61-943b-f9876521e521","request_id":"req_011CcQB9Gg1epoLwytxGa33Q"}
